    Hacker Cup 2019 Qualification Round Solutions
    Facebook Hacker CupÂ·Monday, June 17, 2019
    Here are the solutions to the Hacker Cup 2019 Qualification Round problems. If you had a rejected solution and want to find out where you went wrong, read on and download the official input, output, and solutions!
    Download Input / Output / Solution Files
    The problems in this round were written by Jacob Plachta. Test data was prepared by Wesley May. Solutions and analyses were also contributed by Alex Fetisov and Arnav Sastry.

    Leapfrog: Ch. 1

    Let b be the number of Beta Frogs. Weâll begin by optimally arranging these b Beta Frogs across lilypads 2..N, noting that any such arrangement is possible to achieve regardless of their particular initial positions. Once we settle on an arrangement, weâll proceed to hopefully have the Alpha Frog make one or more leaps starting from lilypad 1 and ending at lilypad N.
    Any arrangement of Beta Frogs consists of zero or more contiguous sequences of frogs, separated by unoccupied lilypads. Each contiguous sequence of x Beta Frogs allows the Alpha Frog to advance by x + 1 lilypads. Another way of thinking about that is that each individual Beta Frog allows the Alpha Frog to advance by either 2 lilypads (if itâs the final Beta Frog in a sequence), or 1 lilypad otherwise. This suggests that the minimum total number of lilypads by which the Alpha Frog can advance is b + 1, while the maximum number is 2 * b. We can then claim that the Alpha Frog can advance by the required total of exactly N - 1 lilypads if and only if b + 1 â¤ N - 1 and N - 1 â¤ 2 * b â in other words, if and only if âN / 2â â¤ b â¤ N - 2. Intuitively, this lower bound corresponds to spacing out Beta Frogs in as many single-frog sequences as possible (e.g. AB.B.B.B. or AB.B.B.BB.), while the upper bound corresponds to filling all but the first and last lilypads with Beta Frogs (e.g. ABBBBB.).

    Leapfrog: Ch. 2

    As in Leapfrog: Ch. 1, if there are b Beta Frogs, the Alpha Frog can still reach lilypad N if âN / 2â â¤ b â¤ N - 2. If b > N - 2, itâs still impossible, as lilypad N must be occupied by a Beta Frog. However, it may now additionally be possible even when b < âN / 2â.
    Letâs consider what the Alpha Frog and two Beta Frogs can accomplish when working together. Weâll take an initial state with N = 5 and b = 2, and consider the following sequence of moves:
    1. AB.B.
    2. .BAB.
    3. .B.BA
    4. ..BBA
    5. .ABB.
    Observe that this sequence has allowed the Alpha Frog to advance by one lilypad, while keeping both Beta Frogs to the right of it! This effectively returns us the initial state, just with N reduced by 1. More lilypads and more Beta Frogs donât prevent this sequence, suggesting that it may be expanded to allow the Alpha Frog to eventually reach lilypad N whenever N â¥ 5 and b â¥ 2.
    Bringing everything together, we can state that itâs possible if and only if min{ 2, âN / 2â } â¤ b â¤ N - 2.

    Mr. X

    If the expression already evaluates to a constant value (â0â or â1â), then the answer is clearly 0.
    Otherwise, if the expression is a single term (âxâ or âXâ), then the answer is clearly 1.
    Otherwise, weâre left with the only non-trivial case â the expression is of the form â([expression][operator][expression])" and evaluates to a variable value (âxâ or âXâ). Each of the two sub-expressions surrounding the top-level operator evaluates to some value (â0â, â1â, âxâ, or âXâ). We can observe that, for any of the 16 possible pairs of values that these sub-expressions can have, there exists at least one operator which causes them to evaluate to a constant value:
    • If one of them is â0â then â&â can be used
    • Otherwise, if one of them is â1â, then â|â can be used
    • Otherwise, both are variable values, and â^â can be used
    Therefore, given that we can just change the top-level operator accordingly, the answer in this case is always 1!
    As such, the whole problem has been reduced to determining whether the expression already evaluates to a constant value. This is equivalent to evaluating the expression twice, with x fixed first to 0 and then to 1, and checking whether the two resulting values are equal. This can be done in O(N) time in a number of fairly well-known ways, such as with a recursive descent parser or with the shunting-yard algorithm.

    Trees as a Service

    Our approach will involve a recursive function which takes a set of nodes S and constructs a tree out of them (if possible), while satisfying all constraints i for which X_i, Y_i and Z_i are all in S.
    Overall, weâll consider each possible node r in S to be the root of the tree, and consider all relevant constraints to either partition the remaining nodes into subtrees under r or determine that it canât work out. Each constraint i falls into one of the following three categories:
    1. X_i = r or Y_i = r â If Z_i = r, then the constraint will definitely be satisfied, while if Z_i â  r, the constraints will definitely not be satisfied and we must abort.
    2. Z_i = r â Nodes X_i and Y_i must be in different subtrees.
    3. Z_i â  r â Nodes X_i, Y_i, and Z_i must all be in the same subtree.
    We can use floodfill to partition the nodes into subtrees based on the category-3 constraints; we should only group nodes into the same subtrees when necessary, as it cannot be more beneficial to otherwise group extra nodes together. We can then check whether any of the category-2 constraints have been violated by the partition.
    As soon as we find a node r which results in a valid set of subtrees as described above, we should fix it as the root and recursively construct each of those subtrees (if possible). Note that itâs insufficient to only consider the first root which satisfies the basic requirements of the category-1 constraints â all three categories must be considered when selecting a root. If any of its subtrees fail to be constructed due to future constraints, however, we should terminate rather than backtracking and considering more possible roots r, as any other choice of root would not yield a meaningfully different partition of subtrees which would avoid violating those same future constraints â the same combination of conflicting constraints present together in that invalid subtree would still end up being present together at some point in the construction process.
    We recurse O(N) times in total (with no backtracking). Each time, we consider O(N) possible roots for the current tree, and for each of those, we spend O(N+M) considering the constraints and partitioning the nodes into subtrees via floodfill. This results in a time complexity of O(NÂ² (N+M)).
